entry.title: arc: Update list of extensions supported by ArcFileSystemWatcherService
entry.content:
ArcFileSystemWatcherService maintains a list of file extension supported

by MediaProvider, and it skips sending media scan request to ARC when a

newly created or modified file's extension is not in the list.

The current list of supported extension is outdated as it was taken from

aosp-nougat codebase. This CL updates it with the supported extensions

entry.title: [Extensions] Apply extension permissions immediately on UI request.
entry.content:
Currently there are multiple scenarios where we apply permissions on a

user request in the UI, and popup a bubble with a "Reload" button will

occur if the page needs to reload in order to properly apply the

permissions change. But a user can dismiss this and select the

"Reload this page" button and the permission will not be applied. This

can cause confusion especially where a user might want to revoke an

extension's permissions and later realized the extension is still

running when they do this.



To match this setting change to how other chrome settings apply we'll be

applying the permission request immediately on user UI request (instead

of deferred to after the "Reload" bubble is accepted) in multiple

scenarios:



* On-click in the toolbar (clicking the extension's icon when it wants

access)

* Changing the permissions from the context menu (bug reporter's

scenario)

* Allowing multiple extensions active tab permission (similar to #1, but

can grant for multiple permissions and is controlled by the

ExtensionsMenuAccessControl flag[1])



This now makes it so whether the user clicks the "Reload this page"

button or the reload bubble acceptance it makes no difference to the

permission being applied.



However, obviously, the page will still need

to be reloaded if this is required for the extension to work as

expected (run all scripts, block web request going forward, etc.) or to

ensure permission is fully revoked in all places. So, as before, an

extension can "partially" run meaning non-blocked actions will run while

blocked actions will be held back until page reload. An example of this

is the Adblock plus extension which will start counting blocked adds in

it's badge text, but ads on the page will not be removed since that

functionality is a blocked action (probably a script injected on

document start).



UI mock ups (google-internal):

https://docs.google.com/presentation/d/1UA3STu8DqtQ5FumyPX-PwKFgnoCZ9-45t9LUJMOiDkE/



[1]: https://source.chromium.org/chromium/chromium/src/+/main:extensions/common/extension_features.cc;l=91-93;drc=1a7cebd3b866379d8955857853102192199c2fc4

file.

WebMessageListener to AndroidX boundary. All changes are still behind

used in prod (behind DEV suffix).

flag. (Right now JS -> Java ArrayBuffer is behind feature flag).

- AndroidX->WebView: Add new 'postMessageWithPayload' method to

'JsReplyProxy', the existing one only accepts string. Same changes in

AndroidX are required later.

tests.

ArrayBuffer tests will be added in AndroidX when feature is

entry.title: Fix resize issue in snapped state
entry.content:
The behaviour of restoring bounds from the window verison history was

ambiguous which led to some pretty confusing behaviours. In general, we

always want to take the restore bounds from the head of the version

history, but we currently also allow for a special case where if the

current state is encountered in the history, we will override the

current restore bounds.



It seems like this case is a special provision for the minimize to

unminimize case, because the restore bounds is overloaded in that case

(where the restore bounds is used to store the windows actual bounds).

This is problematic when combined with horizontal or vertical maximize

which actually relies on the restore bounds to store the "actual"

restore bounds.



The code is now restructured with the following rules:



1. We always take the restore bounds from the head of history.

2. If no bounds exists, we clear the restore bounds.

3. If an override is provided, we will ignore the window state history

and use that instead. (This is currently only used by minimize atm).



This also fixes a small bug in the pruning logic where we might possibly

get an incorrect history chain depending on whether or not we add a new

restore state to the history. This is because we did not change what

target we used to check whether or restore is possible depending on

whether or not we are adding a new restore state.



Fixed: 1427451

entry.content:
MediaDrm.getKeyRequest and MediaDrm.provideKeyResponse may throw

NotProvisionedException if the origin needs re-provision. When this

licenses cleanup.



In this path, we'll unprovision the origin when this happens. The

current MediaDrm instance is still unusable, but the next MediaDrm

creation can properly trigger the provision flow.

entry.title: Launch calc instead of notepad
entry.content:
Two tests in sbox_unittests have always used notepad as a convenient and

harmless child process, however on Windows 11 this becamse more

complicated. When c:\Windows\System32\notepad.exe is launched it is

redirected to the WindowsApps version of notepad. If this version is not

installed then CreateProcessW(..., L"notepad", ...) will fail.



Launching c:\Windows\System32\notepad.exe manually from a command

prompt in this scenario will succeed, launching the old notepad, so

there appears to be some black magic in the process creation path.



Rather than worrying about the details it is better to remove the

dependency on notepad and instead use calc.



Using test_child_process.exe was considered but this is problematic

because GetProcessBaseAddress relies on WaitForInputIdle and therefore

requires a GUI app as its child process.



A buggy assumption in GetModuleList() was found and fixed as well.

entry.title: A fragment can only be monolithic if it's the only one.
entry.content:
How can something be monolithic, if the node creates more than one

fragment? Then it's fragmented. Not monolithic.



Therefore, only mark a fragment as monolithic if block fragmentation is

forced off when at the first (and thus only) fragment.



This replaces the code changes in CL:4422851, which wasn't sufficient,

and also introduced some problems on its own. That CL made it so that we

wouldn't miss OOF fragments when searching for them during pre-paint.

This would cause the code in

FragmentPaintPropertyTreeBuilder::UpdatePaintOffset() to act up, when

setting the PaintPropertyTreeBuilderFragmentContext::

is_in_block_fragmentation flag. There's a similar check for

monolithicness there (but without the non-first-fragment check), and it

would just go ahead and treat a non-first fragment of a containing block

as monolithic, even though such OOF fragments would be direct

descendants of a fragmentainer, which in turn would mess up the paint

offset in FragmentPaintPropertyTreeBuilder::SwitchToOOFContext().



The test included would fail without CL:4422851, then fail differently

with that CL applied, and now, with this CL, it will pass. :) The test

expects the containing block to be split into two fragments, and its

second fragment to be pushed below a float that was forced into the

second column.

entry.title: X509Certificate: harmonize when sanity checking is applied to intermediates
entry.content:
The sanity checking of intermediates is currently inconsistently

applied, with some ways of creating an X509Certificate enforcing it

and others not.



In most cases this sanity checking of the intermediates by

X509Certificate is pointless (when anything actually uses the

intermediates they'll need to do much more parsing/checking than that

anyway). It only really exists since CreateCertificateListFromBytes and

CreateCertBuffersFromBytes can try to parse certificates from different

file formats and use the sanity check to determine if the file format

was correct or not. Make those methods call an internal function that

does the sanity checking, and remove the use of the sanity checking from

all other cases.

entry.title: [Thumbnail Cache] Tweaks and Polish
entry.content:
Split ETC1 and JPEG to have separate file task runners. They never

use the same file name so there should be no contention.



Also just some "drive-by" improvements while looking over the code.



While working on this CL I attempted to collapse Write and Compress

into the same method to avoid thread hoping, but concluded it was

worse to do that via benchmarking. Issues arose due to:

* Compress time >> Write time so moving compression onto the

file_task_runner everything gets a lot slower.

* To avoid the above issue it is possible to create a file and pass it

to another thread that allows blocking to compress and write all at

once. This adds back a thread hop, but is still efficient. However, if

something fails the deletion also has to happen on the

file_task_runner resulting in two hops and another check.

* The prior solution is maginally (7%) faster when there are multiple

parallel writes as there is less contention on the file_task_runner.

However, this was a benchmark that wrote 1000 small filtes in parallel

and in production the ThumbnailCache limits parallel writes to 5 in

the ThumbnailCache which makes this benefit minimal (see

default_write_queue_size in values.xml).

* The above solution also has a problem where an empty file exists for

a time which might need to be read. This could be addressed by having

the ThumbnailCache track current writes, and defer those reads

(something I am considering to remove ETC1 decompression), but this

gets complicated quickly.

entry.title: [GridNG] Introduce CreateConstraintSpaceForSubgridAlgorithm
entry.content:
Previously we relied on `CreateConstraintSpaceForLayout` to create the

constraint space of a subgrid; for subgridded axes, the containing grid

area size is forced as its fixed available size, but this might not be

correct for standalone axis, where we may need to use a different

available size, e.g., when there's a specified width/height.



This was an issue because we want to force the fixed available size for

both axes when we size a subgrid's track collections, otherwise we might

end up calling `ComputeMinMaxSizes` with no subgridded columns/rows.



This change also introduces `SubtractMarginsFromAvailableSize` to adjust

the fixed available space to account for a subgrid's margins.



Baseline tests were regressed due to newly uncovered crashes, which will

be addressed in the follow-up CL:4422414.

entry.title: [Extensions] Use BrowserContextID in more places.
entry.content:
This expands the usage of this typedef to the map of rules registries.

Since we only use the BrowserContext pointer as a key into this map,

using BrowserContextID avoids the chance we might use a dangling

pointer.



This also cleans up a few more things:



1. The GetBrowserContextID function is now inline. There is no reason

for this to be otherwise, since the compiler will completely optimize

out any calls.



2. The implementation of GetBrowserContextID was not compliant with

the C standard regarding casting between pointers and std::uintptr_t.

The standard states that it is only guaranteed that casting from

void* to std::uinptr_t will work, so an intermediate cast to void*

is required.



This is a cleanup CL to prepare for breaking up the event router.

entry.title: chromeos: Fix DumpWithoutCrashing during login restart to apply flags
entry.content:
Chrome's flags at the login screen can be set by policy or by the device

owner account. If a user signs in to an account with different flags

set, chrome restarts to apply the new flags.



This causes a shutdown where the user is signed in, but the primary

profile may not be loaded yet. Some shutdown code related to caching

the app locale calls ProfileManager::GetPrimaryUserProfile(), which

then triggers a DumpWithoutCrashing().



Fix this by avoiding GetPrimaryUserProfile() and instead explicitly

checking if the profile exists from BrowserContextHelper.
